entry.title: Make CSSMathExpressionOperation::HasPercentage not count anchor queries and calc-size() keywords.
entry.content:
This accounts for the possibility that kCalcLengthFunction (previously

known as kCalcPercentLength) does not signal the presence of

percentages. In particular, the category can be kCalcLengthFunction

because of mixing of lengths and percentages, because of anchor queries,

and because of calc-size() keywords.



This also adds comments explaining the difference between HasPercentage

and InvolvesLayout (previously InvolvesPercentage).



This also fixes HasPercentage to propagate the percentage only from the

basis argument of the calc-size() and not from the calculation argument.



This fixes problems for calc-size() animations, which could end up

including percentages when they should not, which would break layouts

when there was no value for the percentages to resolve against.

entry.title: [UPMLocalPwd] Allow calls to the account store during migration
entry.content:
Because the PasswordStore is a profile keyed service, it has to be

created from the first time it's requested. During the local passwords

migration (which also enables the split between account and profile store), both stores will exist, but the expectation was that

the account store wouldn't be invoked. However, there are no checks

in the callers of the store that explicitly verify if the split has

completed. Instead, the account store should allow certain calls, but react as it usually does when the user is not syncing, which is to act

empty.



Note: The migration is only started for local passwords, which means

the user isn't syncing.

entry.title: Reuse SelectorCheckingContext between calls to CollectMatchingRulesForListInternal().
entry.content:
Most calls to CollectMatchingRulesForListInternal() are called

with a list of just a single element, and many of them do not even

hit the selector checker. Given this, it is actually some overhead

to initialize the (now rather large) SelectorCheckingContext object

on the stack. Pull it out so that it can be reused, giving a small

speed boost.



The logical extension of this would be to move it even further out,

becoming part of SelectorChecker, but for some reason, that did not

entry.title: Reland #3: "[A11y] Stable ids for AXObjects with DOM nodes"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 01466963a42b3bd5fdbe5bc5ac17bff6304b058d

Reland #1 was reverted because TAST test inputs.VirtualKeyboardAccent

still fails sometimes.

Reland #2 was reverted because of failing mac test:

DumpAccessibilityEventsTest.AccessibilityEventsAriaComboBoxNext

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/mac11-arm64-rel-tests/34319/overview

https://ci.chromium.org/ui/p/chromium/builders/ci/mac13-arm64-rel-tests/17422/overview

This occurred because we accidentally picked up a

flaky test result via rebase_dump_accessibility_tree_test.py.



Original change's description:

Reland: [A11y] Stable ids for AXObjects with DOM nodes



Reland of CL:4027071. The revert was caused because of the breaking

of a TAST test. Basically, some code in AXTreeSerializer that deleted

subtrees of old child ids is not triggered as often, because if the

DOM node doesn't change, the child ID doesn't. That's a good thing

usually, but if the node is reattached with new style, we need to

make sure its children are reconsidered. The fix is that in the

specific case where a node is reattached, call ChildrenChanged() instead

of just marking it dirty -- in

AXObjectCacheImpl::UpdateCacheAfterNodeIsAttached().



----



Use the DOM node for the AXID for any AXObject with a DOM node.

Other AXObjects will still generate their AXID, but in their own

numerical namespace. For now, any AXID < 0 will be a generated ID.



Role changes and alerts required some new browser-side code, because

rather than the object being destroyed and created with a new id,

the ID now stays the same.



In some cases, test results have improved, e.g. rather than an object

being destroyed and created with a different ID, it retains the same ID

and a change event is fired for it.



Benefits:

- Removes over 100 lines of implementation code

- Use less memory: removes ids_in_use_ (set) and

node_object_mapping_ (map).

- Reduce map lookups when an AXObject is removed -- based on the ID

value, we can determine whether it has a DOM node and if it doesn't,

we already know it cannot be in some of the maps

- Make it easier for screen readers to maintain the user's point of

regard within content, even when the layout or role changes. Users

sometimes lose their place, as the screen reader may move the user

to the top. A hope is that this will reduce the occurrences of that

happening. It may even be possible for screen readers to keep their

place in tabs where the AX tree is released from memory and later

regenerated, which could open up possibilities to using less memory.

- Enable the follow-ups listed below.



Follow-up work:

- Refactor content-visibility: auto change handling in a11y

(crbug.com/1380449).

- See if the dom_node_id field in AXNodeData is needed anymore now

that any id >0 is the same as the dom node id.

- Look at simplifying or removing reparenting computations in

AXTreeSerializer. Maybe we can get rid of expensive

AnyDescendantIsReparented().

- Merge GetAXID() and GetExistingAXID() -- see TODO.

entry.title: [Private Network Access] Store redirect info when redirect mode is manual
entry.content:
When a redirected navigation request needs a preflight because of

Private Network Access, the redirect_info is not properly stored in

CorsURLLoader. In FollowRedirect, the request URL and methods, etc will

be overwritten with the stored redirect_info which is currently empty,

causing the ERR_INVALID_URL in the associated bug.



This CL stores the redirect_info properly for this case.



The "missing cors headers" test cases are expected to fail because

kPrivateNetworkAccessForNavigationsWarningOnly is by default enabled so

requests actually succeeds

.

When kPrivateNetworkAccessForNavigations is disabled

(virtual/pna-navigations-disabled), the preflight aren't sent so we

expect failures too.

entry.title: Use ReadData() instead of BeginReadData()
entry.content:
This is a preliminary change to split ReadAndWrite() method in

ServiceWorkerRaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderClient.



At a high-level, the current ReadAndWrite() operations are following:

1. Begin read operation.

2. Write data to another buffer.

3. End read operation.



This operation requires the read data pipe API call twice (1 and 3), and

that makes the function separation difficult.



This CL updates ReadAndWrite() not to read data via two phase approach,

but use ReadData() and store the buffer data in the class.



After this CL, the read operation is completed at once, and the new data

won't be stored unless all buffered data in the member are consumed.

entry.title: Layout: Fix a crash in AppendText()
entry.content:
When we update the content of a Text node, we do:

1. Update Text::data_

2. Call InlineNode::SetTextWithOffset()

3. Update LayoutText::text_ with transformation



In SetTextWithOffset(), we call InlineNodeDataEditor::Prepare(), which

might build an OffsetMapping with InlineItemsBuilderTemplate. It

expects that LayoutText::TransformedText() is based on the text before

step 1.



So, we must not transform OriginalText() on the fly in

InlineItemsBuilderTemplate because OriginalText() is Text::data_. We

need to record TextOffsetMap which was generated for LayoutText::text_.



This CL introduces a new struct `VariableLengthTransformResult`, which

contains a TextOffsetMap instance and an original text length. It's

per-LayoutText object, but is stored in LayoutView because storing it in

each of LayoutText increases memory consumption.

entry.title: [Audio] Propagate socket errors to sinks and sources. Prevent reuse.
entry.content:
If the browser side closes the socket the renderer is only notified

through a failure to read from the socket. This error was being dropped

instead of propagated to the RenderCallback and CaptureCallback.



This error signal is then used to prevent reuse of AudioRendererMixer

instances. This fixes the linked issue (same-origin navigations where

the mixer is reused between navigations).



There may still be constructions where a RenderFrame which creates a

shared sink is closed while the sink is being used. I haven't yet been

able to construct such a scenario though.

entry.title: Revert "Fix wrong PLSA::ShouldScrollOnMainThread after CSS overflow change"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 30753ceb52480bd80aef5e755885d7b79648e108.



Reason for revert: Now MainThreadScrollingDidChange() is not called.

We need to verify if it's OK to call UpdateCompositorAnimations()

without calling MainThreadScrollingDidChange() (which seems to do

more than UpdateCompositorAnimations() does).

Revert first for safety.



Original change's description:

> Fix wrong PLSA::ShouldScrollOnMainThread after CSS overflow change

>

> Previously PLSA::SetShouldScrollOnMainThread() was called only for

> user-scrollable scrollable areas, and missed the case when a

> composited composited scrollable area became not user-scrollable

> (and not-composited), causing wrong scroll animation running on the

> wrong thread.

>

> Now remove PLSA::SetShouldScrollOnMainThread() and let

> PLSA::ShouldScrollOnMainThread() always return the correct status.

> In most cases the function is not called at all, or just once for

> each animating scroller, so the new code actually costs less.

>

- TouchAccessibilityEnabler::OnTimer

-> AccessibilityManager::OnTwoFingersTouch[Start|Stop]

-> extensions::EventRouter::BroadcastEvent(accessibility_private_on_two_fingers_start_or_stop_event)

-> Meet app js calls

chrome.accessibilityFeatures.spokenFeedback.set

- TouchAccessibilityEnabler::OnTimer

entry.title: media/gpu/V4L2StatefulVD: use SingleThreadTaskRunner for event poll
entry.content:
V4L2StatefulVD uses a SequencedTaskRunner from a pool to block while

waiting for events from the V4L2 driver. Said pool can and usually

does reuse the actual thread servicing the TaskRunner; when there are

multiple video decodes in parallel, eventually they'll block each

other. This is found by Tast tests e.g. like h264_720p_30fps_hw_3x3.

This CL fixes that by using SingleThreadTaskRunners instead. A similar

situation was found and fixed with a CL similar to this in

https://crrev.com/c/5253818.

entry.title: Fix wrong PLSA::ShouldScrollOnMainThread after CSS overflow change
entry.content:
Previously PLSA::SetShouldScrollOnMainThread() was called only for

user-scrollable scrollable areas, and missed the case when a

composited composited scrollable area became not user-scrollable

(and not-composited), causing wrong scroll animation running on the

wrong thread.



Now remove PLSA::SetShouldScrollOnMainThread() and let

PLSA::ShouldScrollOnMainThread() always return the correct status.

In most cases the function is not called at all, or just once for

each animating scroller, so the new code actually costs less.
